      {
        "id": 269919,
        "name": "Laura",
        "username": "lauraann87",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/lauraann87/{size}/52542_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-06-17T12:43:31.981Z",
        "cooked": "<h3><a name=\"p-269919-summary-1\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-269919-summary-1\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>Summary</h3>\n<p>Please consider adding an <strong>‚ÄúUse system font‚Äù</strong> toggle to Signal Desktop (Linux), similar to how Proton Mail handles this in their Electron-based desktop app.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3><a name=\"p-269919-why-this-matters-2\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-269919-why-this-matters-2\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>Why This Matters</h3>\n<p>Signal Desktop is built on Electron, but currently does <strong>not respect GTK/system font settings</strong> on Linux, nor provide any way to override the UI font. Users who customise their desktop for accessibility, aesthetics, or readability (e.g., larger or monospaced fonts like <em>FiraCode Nerd Font</em>) are unable to carry those preferences into Signal.</p>\n<p>Meanwhile, other Electron apps like <strong>Proton Mail Desktop</strong> offer this option:</p>\n<p><div class=\"lightbox-wrapper\"><a class=\"lightbox\" href=\"https://community.signalusers.org/uploads/db3609/original/3X/d/4/d421d2a9e97e5485e6b509f0a59ae14fb1674c75.jpeg\" data-download-href=\"https://community.signalusers.org/uploads/db3609/d421d2a9e97e5485e6b509f0a59ae14fb1674c75\" title=\"image\"><img src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/uploads/db3609/optimized/3X/d/4/d421d2a9e97e5485e6b509f0a59ae14fb1674c75_2_690x341.jpeg\" alt=\"image\" data-base62-sha1=\"ugBGIq6gSdFTfdCq26B16uxbVeR\" width=\"690\" height=\"341\" srcset=\"https://community.signalusers.org/uploads/db3609/optimized/3X/d/4/d421d2a9e97e5485e6b509f0a59ae14fb1674c75_2_690x341.jpeg, https://community.signalusers.org/uploads/db3609/optimized/3X/d/4/d421d2a9e97e5485e6b509f0a59ae14fb1674c75_2_1035x511.jpeg 1.5x, https://community.signalusers.org/uploads/db3609/optimized/3X/d/4/d421d2a9e97e5485e6b509f0a59ae14fb1674c75_2_1380x682.jpeg 2x\" data-dominant-color=\"1F1626\"><div class=\"meta\"><svg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><use href=\"#far-image\"></use></svg><span class=\"filename\">image</span><span class=\"informations\">1514√ó750 91.5 KB</span><svg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><use href=\"#discourse-expand\"></use></svg></div></a></div></p>\n<p>This makes Proton Mail much more visually integrated on Linux and friendlier for users with visual or typographic preferences.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3><a name=\"p-269919-proposed-solution-3\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-269919-proposed-solution-3\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>Proposed Solution</h3>\n<p>Under <strong>Preferences &gt; Appearance</strong>, add something like:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"lang-auto\">‚òë Use system font (GTK default)\n</code></pre>\n<p>Optionally, allow manual font selection as an advanced setting ‚Äî but even just following the system default would resolve this request.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3><a name=\"p-269919-additional-context-4\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-269919-additional-context-4\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>Additional Context</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Many users run accessibility themes or monospaced fonts across their environment</li>\n<li>This is especially useful on Linux, where GTK/QT theming is common</li>\n<li>Currently, <code>--custom-css-path</code> is ignored, and DevTools/injection is locked down ‚Äî which is understandable for security, but limits visual flexibility</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3><a name=\"p-269919-benefits-5\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-269919-benefits-5\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>Benefits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Improved accessibility</li>\n<li>More consistent UX across platforms</li>\n<li>Aligns Signal Desktop with Proton Mail and other Electron-based apps that support system theming</li>\n</ul>",
